Introduction ¶

This dataset represents thousands of loans made through Prosper platform which is a peer-to-peer lending marketplace based in San Franciso, California. The dataset contains 113,937 loans with 81 variables on each loan, including loan amount, borrower or interest rate, current loan status, borrower income and many others.

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

There are 113,937 loans in the dataset with 81 features. Most features are numeric (61 features to be precise). The variables Loanstatus, CreditGrade and ProsperRating are categorical variables with the following levels:

  • LoanStatus: Current, Completed, Chargedoff, Defaulted, Past Due(specifying by what period), Cancelled and FinalPaymentInProgress
  • CreditGrade: A, AA, B, C, D, E, HR, NC
  • ProsperRating: A, AA, B,C, D, E, HR

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

I'm interested in figuring out which features are best in:

  • Determining the properties that lead to a higher amount of loan given
  • Looking at the trend of the borrowing vs payment on this lending platform.
  • The effect of the prosper rating and term on the loan amount

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

I expect that the CreditGrade and LoanStatus will affect the loan amount. The better the CreditGrade, the higher the amount of the loan amount. The loan status having an effect on the credit grade. The features that will help support in the investigation are CreditGrade, LoanStatus, LoanNumber and LoanOriginalAmount and a few other features related to the loan applicable. This will be depicted in the created subset of columns created below.

I can now look at distribution of a few of the aforementioned variables

CreditGrade is the credit rating that was assigned at the time the listing went live. Applicable for listings pre-2009 period and will only be populated for those listings.

ProsperRating (Alpha) represents an estimated average annualized loss rate range to investors. The Prosper Rating assigned at the time the listing was created is between AA - HR. Applicable for loans originated after July 2009.

#create a bar chart to show borrowing on a monthly and yearly basis
def month_year_barChart():
    month_order = ['Jan', 'Feb','Mar', 'Apr', 'May','June', 'July', 'Aug', 'Sept', 'Oct', 'Nov', 'Dec']
    year_order = ['2005', '2006', '2007','2008', '2009', '2010', '2011', '2012','2013', '2014']
    
    ordered_month = pd.api.types.CategoricalDtype(ordered=True, categories=month_order)
    ordered_year = pd.api.types.CategoricalDtype(ordered=True, categories=year_order)
    
    new_loan_df['month'] = new_loan_df['month'].astype(ordered_month)
    new_loan_df['year'] = new_loan_df['year'].astype(ordered_year)
    
    fig, ax = plt.subplots(nrows=2, figsize = [8,8])
    
    default_color = sb.color_palette()[0]
    sb.countplot(data = new_loan_df, x = 'month', color = default_color, ax = ax[0])
    sb.countplot(data = new_loan_df, x = 'year', color = default_color, ax = ax[1])
    
month_year_barChart();

January, October, December, February and September are the top 5 months loans were taken. The year 2013 leading in number of borrowers/loans given out.

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. How did the feature(s) of interest vary with other features in the dataset?¶

Most of the relationships between the numeric variables are weakly correlated either negatively or positively. For example, the relationship between loan amount and the other features show a significantly weak negative or positive correlation except the MonthlyLoanPayment at 0.932. This indicates that the higher the loan amount, the more the monthly loan payment which is logical.

There is a linear relationship between applicable loan amount and number of investors funding the loan. But this can be affected by the theory of a few investors funding with more money or vice versa.

The prosper rating also has an effect on the number of investors considering the rating informs potential investors of possible levels of risk in a loan application.

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. Were there features that strengthened each other in terms of looking at your feature(s) of interest?¶

The credit grade rating has an effect on the given loan amount which subsequently affects the APR charged. The length of the loan is a contributing factor to the borrower's monthly loan payment with short term loan attracting more investors than the long term ones.

Were there any interesting or surprising interactions between features?¶

The interaction between the original loan amount and the annual % rate to the borrower whereby the higher the amount of loan given, the lesser the APR incurred.

Conclusions ¶

  • The original loan amount is the most important factor when it comes to deciding on what the monthly loan payment would be. Other factors come into play as well such as Term. As the term increases, the monthly loan payment decreases which is logical.

  • Prosper rating is a factor in attracting investors in the loan application with higher prosper rating attracting more investors to fund the loan. Moreover, short term (12 months) and long term (60 months) loans require a high prosper rating in order to attract more investors.

  • Status of employment is a factor in the amount of loan a borrower is given which subsequently affects the number of investors funding the applicable loans.

Limitation¶

  • The dataset was intense with many variables. I created a subset to work with the necessary features for data exploration.
